@Don H
Here's the shocker: "The Merchant of Venice" is classed as a comedy. The humiliation and forced conversion of Shylock were uproarious for the Bard's audience,  and of course the lovers have their happy ending.
Needless to say, some here may view it differently.

@Nora
See if you can find Harry Golden's essay on the play (in his newletter The Carolina Israelite, then collected into 2 books [one is "For Two Cents Plain" and I have forgotten the other]).
  Golden's take is that while yes, on one level he is playing anti-Jew stuff for cheap laughs, on another he is showing it up. Shylock is given a genuine grievance and gets that powerful "Hath not a Jew eyes...." speech and the guy who borrows the money is doing it for the grubby motive of wooing a rich girl--when Shakespeare could surely have given him a nice noble one.

@ad absurdum Just to be clear, Nixon didn‚Äôt create the EPA out of any concern for the environment.  He did it due to overwhelming public pressure.  You can read about it in the Bill Ruckleshaus interview here:  

<a href="https://www.epa.gov/archive/epa/aboutepa/william-d-ruckelshaus-oral-history-interview.html" target="_blank">https://www.epa.gov/archive/epa/aboutepa/william-d-ruckelshaus-oral-history-interview.html</a>

In fact, Nixon tried to water down the original Clean Air Act, but Muskie won out.  And Nixon vetoed the original Clean Water Act.

